faq:
  - q: "How long should a resume be?"
    a: "One page for professionals with under 8 years of experience. Two pages for professionals with 8 or more years of relevant experience. Three pages only for executives or academics with extensive publication or leadership records. Page count is not the goal — density and relevance are. Every line should earn its space."
  - q: "What should a resume include?"
    a: "A resume should include: (1) Contact information and LinkedIn URL at the top. (2) A brief professional summary (2–3 sentences). (3) Work experience in reverse chronological order with impact-led bullet points. (4) Education. (5) Skills section with specific tools and technologies. Optionally: certifications, publications, or a featured projects section for technical roles."
  - q: "How do I make my resume stand out?"
    a: "The resumes that stand out lead with impact, not activity. Every bullet should answer: what changed because of what you did? Quantify outcomes — revenue, users, latency, cost, time. Make your seniority legible in the first 6 seconds by leading with title, company tier, and scope. ATS keyword alignment matters but is secondary to signal clarity."
  - q: "How do I write resume bullets that get noticed?"
    a: "Use the formula: [Action verb] + [what you did] + [specific result with number]. Example: 'Redesigned the payment checkout flow, reducing cart abandonment by 18% and increasing monthly revenue by $340K.' Avoid: responsibilities-led bullets like 'Responsible for managing the checkout flow.' Responsibility is not accomplishment."
  - q: "Should I use a resume template?"
    a: "A clean, simple template is fine. Avoid heavily designed templates with columns, graphics, or headers in text boxes — these fail ATS parsing. Use a single-column format with clear section headers. Font: 10–12pt serif or clean sans-serif. Margins: 0.5–1 inch. White space improves readability without wasting page space."
  - q: "How do I tailor my resume to a job description?"
    a: "Read the job description and identify the 8–12 most important keywords and skills. Make sure those terms appear naturally in your resume — in your summary, bullets, and skills section. ATS systems scan for keyword density before any human sees your resume. Mirror the language of the job description without copy-pasting — rephrase naturally."
  - q: "What is ATS and how do I optimize my resume for it?"
    a: "ATS stands for Applicant Tracking System — the software companies use to filter resumes before human review. To pass ATS: use standard section headers (Work Experience, Education, Skills), avoid tables and columns, use the exact keywords from the job description, and submit as a .docx or PDF (check which format is preferred). Approximately 75% of resumes are rejected by ATS before a human sees them."
howto:
  name: "How to Write a Resume Step by Step"
  steps:
    - name: "Choose the right format"
      text: "Use a reverse-chronological format — current or most recent role at the top, working backward. This is the default expectation for most hiring managers and ATS systems. Functional or hybrid formats raise red flags and fail most ATS parsing. One column, standard section headers, no tables or graphics."
    - name: "Write a professional summary (2–3 sentences)"
      text: "Your summary is the first thing a recruiter reads. Lead with your title and level, name your domain or specialization, and signal what you are targeting. Example: 'Senior data engineer with 8 years of experience building real-time data platforms at scale. Specializing in streaming pipelines, data quality systems, and platform modernization. Targeting staff-level roles at product-led companies with complex data infrastructure.'"
    - name: "Build your work experience section"
      text: "For each role: Company name, your title, dates (month/year), and 4–6 bullet points. Bullets should lead with an action verb and end with a quantified result. Include scope signals: team size, revenue impact, user count, system scale. More recent roles get more bullets. Roles older than 10 years get 2–3 bullets or can be listed without bullets."
    - name: "Write impact-led bullet points"
      text: "Use the formula: [Strong action verb] + [what you built, changed, or led] + [specific result]. Avoid: 'Responsible for...', 'Worked on...', 'Helped with...'. These describe activity, not accomplishment. Every bullet should answer: what would have been worse without your contribution?"
    - name: "Optimize for ATS keywords"
      text: "Copy the job description into a text file. Identify the 10 most important skills, tools, and phrases. Make sure every one of them appears at least once in your resume — in context, not in a keyword dump. Pay attention to exact phrasing: 'machine learning' vs 'ML' vs 'artificial intelligence' may be treated differently by ATS parsers."
    - name: "Add a skills section"
      text: "List specific tools, languages, platforms, and methodologies — not generic skills like 'communication' or 'leadership.' These belong in your bullet points with evidence. Your skills section is primarily for ATS keyword matching. Example: Python, SQL, Apache Spark, Databricks, dbt, Airflow, AWS, Snowflake."
    - name: "Proofread and format for scannability"
      text: "Recruiters spend 6–10 seconds on the first pass. Make sure your name, current title, and company are immediately visible at the top. Bold or emphasize key metrics in bullets. Use consistent date formatting. No typos, no passive voice, no unexplained abbreviations. Test ATS compatibility by copying into a plain text file — everything should be readable."
